      {
        "id": 3166568,
        "name": "Don Cornutt",
        "username": "dcornutt",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/dcornutt/{size}/562_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-05-20T22:48:47.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I have heard so much about dilute 2018 whites. Don\u2019t buy them.  The year is a pass.  Etc etc.</p>\n<p>I have several that I would put up against many of the best vintages of recent years.  They are delicious.</p>\n<p>I want to give a special shout out to two producers.   The first is Henri Germain.  The 2018s from Germain are concentrated.  Focused.  They show less reduction than prior years so they are very approachable.  Great freshness and perceived acidity on the finish.  Delicious.  Bravo!</p>\n<p>The producer that deserves special kudos in 2018 is Ramonet.</p>\n<p>The Ruchottes is magic.  Very mineral and totally delicious out of the gate.  Long and I am sure will age on the balance.  This might be the best Ruchottes in my years of drinking Ramonet.  Better than 2017 or 2014.  Better than 2010.  Those are really good too!  A premier cru legend in the making to me.  I served this to some Burgundy neophytes.  They were blown away by the mineral character and balance.</p>\n<p>The next is the Boudriottes.  The 2018 Boudriottes is crystalline with just a hint of that honeycomb reduction and barrel note.  Perfect density and EXTREMELY fresh midpalate.  Amazing finish.  Again, those giving up on 2018 will be sorry to miss Ramonet.  A spectacular wine.</p>\n<p>Just a few observations on 2018 whites.</p>",
