      {
        "id": 3166716,
        "name": "Fred Daniels",
        "username": "Fred_Daniels",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/fred_daniels/{size}/1226_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-05-21T04:50:35.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>\u201cOff vintages are just what we drink while waiting for the great vintages to mature\u201d is what I always heard.  I have been wonderfully surprised by many \u201coff vintage\u201d bottlings\u2026to my mind they just drink well earlier.  Maybe not as concentrated or nuanced, but perfectly ready in 5-10 years instead of 20-30.</p>\n<p>Off vintage wines used to be sold at a discount and could represent good \u201cvalue\u201d but I don\u2019t think that is the case any more.  I\u2019d drink any of the wines mentioned here, but if I was going to plunk down $$$ for a Ramonet Batard I would be inclined to put them towards the 2017 or 2014 rather than the 2018.  Maybe wait for these to go on \u201ccloseout\u201d\u2026  <img src=\"/images/emoji/unicode/slight_smile.png?v=12\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\"></p>",
